            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Robert Kenji Miller\u2019s life story is etched into the very hills of San Francisco he traverses daily. Born in Daly City to an American engineer father and a Japanese immigrant mother, he was a bridge between two worlds. Growing up, he felt the pull of both sides: the quiet grace of his mother\u2019s traditions and the ambitious drive of post-war American suburbia. To succeed, he chose to lean into the latter, embracing \"Robert\" over the \"Kenji\" his mother favored.\n\nA practical and disciplined student, he earned a Bachelor's in Business Administration from UC Berkeley. He graduated directly into the frenetic energy of the late '90s dot-com boom. While others chased fleeting startup glory, Robert found his calling in the structured world of management consulting, helping bring order to the chaos. He worked relentlessly, his strategic mind and tireless work ethic earning him a steady ascent. He made partner before he was 40, a pinnacle of professional achievement.\n\nThe key turning point in his life was not a promotion, but a divorce. At 48, his wife of fifteen years left, telling him, \"You optimize businesses for a living, but you never found the time to optimize us.\" The words struck him harder than any failed business deal. It was a catalyst for introspection, forcing him to confront the personal cost of his professional success.\n\nToday, Robert\u2019s life is one of curated success. He lives in a minimalist Nob Hill condo with sweeping views of the bay. His daily routine is precise: a 6 AM workout, followed by a 3.8-mile Uber ride to his Financial District office, during which he clears his morning emails. He appreciates San Francisco for its world-class dining and cultural offerings, yet often feels like an observer behind glass, his connections to the city transactional rather than communal.\n\nHis aspirations have shifted. The hunger for career dominance has been sated, replaced by a yearning for connection. He dreams of finally taking a sabbatical to visit his mother's small hometown near Kyoto, to learn the language he let fade, and to reconnect with the Kenji he left behind. Robert Kenji Miller has conquered the professional world; his next, and perhaps greatest, challenge is to conquer the distance within himself."
