            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was eight. In their Daly City kitchen, his mother offered him a bowl of rice. \"For you, Kenji,\" she\u2019d said, smiling. \"My name is Robert,\" he corrected, wanting to sound like the other boys at school. The light in her eyes flickered out, replaced by a quiet nod. He felt a flash of victory then, a small assertion of his American side. Now, he only remembers it as the first time he chose a title over a connection, the day he asked his own mother to forget his name.\n\n2.\nIt was 2 AM in 1998. From a conference room high above SoMa, he watched the city thrum with dot-com energy. Below, launch parties burned through venture capital. On his screen was a flawless spreadsheet, a model of efficiency that would save a flailing company. He felt a surge of clean, quiet power\u2014not from the speculative frenzy, but from the absolute certainty of his logic. In that moment, he knew he had found his lane: bringing order to the chaos others created. It felt like purpose.\n\n3.\nHe was thirty-nine when the managing partner called. \"Congratulations, Robert. You\u2019ve made partner.\" He felt a flicker of intellectual satisfaction\u2014the project was complete, the goal achieved. He ended the call and swiveled his chair to face the bay. He had summited the mountain. But instead of elation, a quiet emptiness settled in. He had meticulously planned his ascent for two decades, but had never once considered what he would do with the view from the top. The silence in his office was deafening.\n\n4.\nHe remembers their twelfth anniversary. He was in the office finalizing a merger deck while his wife was at a restaurant, sitting at their table for two. He\u2019d called to say he\u2019d be late, then called again to cancel. \"It\u2019s a critical night,\" he\u2019d insisted. \"So is this,\" she\u2019d replied, her voice flat. He saw it then as a necessary sacrifice for their future. Looking back, he realizes he was trading their present for a future that would never include them both.\n\n5.\nJust last month, at a table for one at Quince. He watched a couple at a nearby table, their hands intertwined, their laughter effortless. He could analyze the meal\u2014the impeccable service, the innovative pairings\u2014as a series of successful data points. He was a connoisseur of the city's best, yet he felt entirely separate from its lifeblood. He was an audience member watching a play about human connection, realizing he had mastered the price of everything, but had forgotten the value of what truly mattered."
